{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\n\nThe plan-review \"Pass-2 verify\" pass takes the findings the finder raised and makes a decisive\nper-finding \"is this real?\" judgment. There are two problems with how it chunks and where it lives,\nand this epic resolves both together with a clean sequencing.\n\n**Problem 1 — token-naive chunking.** The bespoke verifier chunks the findings list by a HARD-CODED\ncount (`pass2_verify(batch_size=12)`, `passes.py`; `range(0, len(findings), 12)`). It is an arbitrary\nmechanical guardrail (introduced in the original plan-review epic 5fd2, commit 2873a916), never\nconfig-driven, token-naive. The workflow-engine gate (the sole verdict producer since the B-RETIRE\ncutover, commit 68dc9713) instead does ONE aggregate verify call over all findings — correct for the\ncommon case, but a pathological huge-findings ticket could exceed the model context window where the\ncount-12 chunk would not. The principled fix is TOKEN-BASED chunking (estimate the verify request vs\nthe selected model's window — like the Pass-1 finder `sizing.py` machinery already does), splitting\nonly when needed, NOT a magic count.\n\n**Problem 2 — a surviving second code path.** The B-RETIRE cutover deleted the bespoke full-review\norchestrator (`run_review`, the `gate_engine` flag, the B4 parity harness, `pass4_coach`), but\n`pass2_verify` / `verifier_cfg` / `_run_passes` are NOT dead: they back the opt-in **progressive\ndrift-refresh** probe (`verify.progressive_drift_refresh`, default off → `orchestrator.drift_refresh`\n→ `_run_passes` → `pass2_verify`). So there are still TWO verify call sites, which is exactly the \"no\ntwo divergent batching rules\" hazard. Rather than maintain a shared chunker across both, we **migrate\ndrift-refresh onto the workflow engine FIRST**, collapsing to a single verify path; the chunking work\nthen becomes a single-site change.\n\n**Decision — verifier model downgrade becomes a declarative per-step `model:` key.** The bespoke\n`verifier_cfg` downgrades the verify pass from the default frontier model (Opus) to a decisive\nnon-frontier model (Sonnet) UNLESS the operator explicitly chose a model. The workflow verify step\ndoes NOT apply this today (it uses the runner default). We reproduce the downgrade declaratively via\nthe existing per-step `model:` key (`resolve_model`, WS-D3: step > workflow > cfg) so the workflow\nverify step pins Sonnet-by-default with operator override preserved. NOTE: the two historical call\nsites sizing against possibly-different models is NOT a blocker for chunking — each site sizes against\nits own resolved model and both are correct; and after the migration there is only one site anyway.\nBecause this makes a per-step `model:` key first-class on a shipped gate workflow, the change must be\nreflected in the **visual workflow editor UX**: the per-step model must be editable in the properties\npanel and must round-trip through BPMN export/import (today only the workflow-level model is carried,\nso editing the workflow in the visual editor could silently DROP a step's model).\n\n## Workstreams (sequenced)\n\n**WS1 — Migrate drift-refresh onto the workflow engine (FIRST), delete the bespoke pipeline.**\n- Add a \"probe mode\" to the plan-review workflow: run find→verify→decide over a restricted criteria\n  subset (`_PROBE_CRITERIA = E4, G1G2`) instead of the full registry (a `criteria` allowlist input on\n  the finder op, or a dedicated `drift-probe.yaml` reusing the same ops/prompts).\n- Expose per-finding decisions + citations in the workflow return shape so the escalation gate can\n  inspect `decision` and `citations[].path` against the drifted-file set.\n- Rewrite `drift_refresh` to wrap the workflow call; keep the non-LLM orchestration in Python\n  (candidate detection, dep re-hash, escalation gate, `refresh_attestation`, synthetic PASS verdict).\n- **Pre-deletion parity gate (expand→contract):** before deleting any bespoke code, run BOTH the\n  workflow probe and the bespoke `_run_passes` probe over a fixture corpus and assert verdict parity\n  (escalate-vs-refresh decision agrees). The deletion is the LAST step of WS1, gated on that parity\n  test passing; until it does, the bespoke path stays behind the (already default-off) drift flag as\n  the back-out.\n- Only after parity holds, DELETE the now-dead bespoke orchestration: `_run_passes`, `pass2_verify`,\n  `verifier_cfg`. Keep the genuinely shared helpers (`pass3_decide`, `pass3_over_findings`,\n  `verify_instructions`, `coach_instructions`, `render_coach_notes`, `load_move_registry`).\n\n**WS2 — Verifier model downgrade as a per-step `model:` key + visual-editor UX.**\n- Pin the workflow verify step's `model:` to the decisive non-frontier verifier (Sonnet) by default,\n  preserving operator override (mirrors `verifier_cfg` semantics declaratively via `resolve_model`).\n- Surface the per-step `model` field in the visual editor properties panel (a select over the known\n  model ladder) and make it round-trip through BPMN export/import so the visual editor never drops a\n  step's model on save.\n- **BPMN back-compat:** import of a pre-existing BPMN document that lacks the per-step model attribute\n  must default gracefully to \"no per-step override\" (the step falls back to the workflow/cfg model via\n  `resolve_model`), never error — legacy exports stay importable.\n- Document the per-step `model:` knob in the workflow-authoring + editor docs.\n\n**WS3 — Principled token-based chunking for the (now single) verify path.** (Depends on WS2: WS3\nsizes against the per-step `model:` window that WS2 pins/resolves.)\n- Replace any count-based batching with a token estimate vs the verify step's resolved model window,\n  reusing `sizing.py` `largest_window_tokens(model)` + the `est_tokens` (chars/4) estimator rather\n  than a new magic constant or a new tokenizer dependency.\n- **Budget formula (explicit):** `budget = floor(largest_window_tokens(model) * HEADROOM)` where\n  `HEADROOM` is a named, config-driven knob (`verify.verify_window_headroom`, default `0.8`) — NOT a\n  hardcoded literal (so we don't replace `batch_size=12` with a different magic number). A chunk fits\n  when `est_tokens(system_prompt + verify_instructions(chunk)) + projected_output(chunk) <= budget`.\n- **Projected output (explicit):** `projected_output(chunk) = len(chunk) * PER_FINDING_VERIFY_TOKENS`,\n  a named constant sized from the `plan_review_verification` schema's per-finding object (a small\n  reserve, ~256 tokens/finding, documented and adjustable) — output scales with finding count, so it\n  is reserved per finding, not as a flat constant.\n- `<= budget` findings → ONE aggregate verify call (unchanged behavior). `> budget` → minimal\n  principled splits that preserve GLOBAL finding enumeration and re-merge by finding `index` (the\n  existing merge contract).\n- **Single-oversized-finding edge case** (one finding alone exceeds the budget): escalate up the ladder\n  starting from the verify step's RESOLVED model — `models_at_or_above(resolved_verify_model)` where\n  `resolved_verify_model` is the WS2 per-step `model:` after any operator override (the same value the\n  budget is computed against), so the escalation base is unambiguous. If it still does not fit at the\n  top of the ladder, mark that finding INDETERMINATE (non-blocking, surfaced) — never silently drop.\n\n**WS4 — Coach-call parity nit (separate task).**\n- Bespoke `pass4_coach` returns `[]` with NO LLM call when there are 0 surviving advisories; the\n  workflow ALWAYS runs the `coach_notes` prompt step (1 wasted coach call on a clean PASS). Gate the\n  workflow `coach_notes` step on `surviving > 0` (a `when:` condition) to match bespoke.\n\n## Design decisions (resolved)\n\n- **Sequencing + dependencies:** WS1 (migration) lands first so chunking is a single-site change and\n  \"no two divergent batching rules\" holds by construction. **WS2 → WS3:** WS3 sizes against the\n  per-step `model:` window that WS2 pins, so WS2 lands before WS3. Riskiest slice first: the WS1\n  migration (verdict-parity risk) and the WS2 BPMN round-trip (serialization-format risk) are the two\n  evidence-gated slices; each ships behind its own parity/round-trip test before the dependent work.\n- **Model downgrade = per-step `model:` key** (declarative, operator-overridable); each verify site\n  sizes against its own resolved model — no cross-path model reconciliation is required.\n- **Editor parity is in scope:** a per-step `model:` on a shipped gate workflow MUST be editable and\n  round-trip-safe in the visual editor (properties panel + BPMN), or editing the workflow there would\n  regress the gate. Legacy BPMN without the attribute imports gracefully (no per-step override).\n- **Token estimator:** reuse `est_tokens` (chars/4) + `largest_window_tokens`; no new dependency. The\n  `> budget` test empirically grounds the chars/4 safety margin (asserts estimate + headroom keeps a\n  real request under the actual window), so the margin is measured, not assumed.\n- **Headroom is a config knob** (`verify.verify_window_headroom`, default `0.8`), not a literal.\n- **Merge semantics:** preserve global enumeration; re-merge by finding `index` (existing contract).\n- **Oversized single finding:** escalate from the resolved verify model, else INDETERMINATE — never\n  silent-drop.\n- **Decomposition:** this epic is a parent; WS1–WS4 become child stories/tasks (WS1 the riskiest\n  vertical slice), each separately plan-reviewed before it is claimed.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Drift-refresh runs entirely through the workflow engine; the bespoke `pass2_verify` /\n  `verifier_cfg` / `_run_passes` orchestration is deleted, leaving ONE verify code path.\n- The workflow verify step applies the Sonnet-by-default verifier model (operator override preserved),\n  and that per-step model is fully editable and round-trip-safe in the visual workflow editor.\n- The workflow verify chunks findings into multiple calls ONLY when the estimated request would exceed\n  the resolved model's window (token-based, reusing the sizing/window machinery); small findings sets\n  remain ONE aggregate call with no behavior change.\n- No magic `batch_size` constant remains anywhere (the headroom fraction is a named config knob).\n- A PASS with 0 surviving advisories makes no coach LLM call.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] **WS1:** `drift_refresh` produces its probe verdict via the workflow engine (find→verify→decide\n      over `E4, G1G2`), not `_run_passes`.\n- [ ] **WS1:** The drift non-LLM orchestration (candidate detection, dep re-hash, escalation on a\n      blocking finding or a finding citing a drifted file, `refresh_attestation`) is preserved.\n- [ ] **WS1:** A parity test asserts the workflow probe and the bespoke probe reach the same\n      escalate-vs-refresh decision over a fixture corpus BEFORE any bespoke code is removed.\n- [ ] **WS1:** The workflow return shape exposes per-finding `decision` + `citations[].path` at the\n      granularity the drift escalation gate requires.\n- [ ] **WS1:** Once the parity test passes, `_run_passes`, `pass2_verify`, and `verifier_cfg` are\n      deleted; no dead bespoke orchestration remains.\n- [ ] **WS1:** The shared helpers (`pass3_decide`, `pass3_over_findings`, `verify_instructions`,\n      coach/move helpers) remain present and are still imported by the workflow ops.\n- [ ] **WS2:** The workflow verify step pins the decisive non-frontier verifier model (Sonnet) by\n      default, resolved via the existing per-step `model:` / `resolve_model` path.\n- [ ] **WS2:** An explicit operator model override is honored on the verify step (parity with the old\n      `verifier_cfg`).\n- [ ] **WS2:** The visual editor properties panel lets a user view/edit a step's `model`.\n- [ ] **WS2:** A per-step `model` survives a BPMN export → import (visual-edit → save) round-trip\n      unchanged; a regression test asserts the round-trip.\n- [ ] **WS2:** Importing a legacy BPMN document that lacks the per-step model attribute succeeds and\n      falls back to the workflow/cfg model (no error, no per-step override).\n- [ ] **WS2:** Authoring + editor docs document the per-step `model:` knob.\n- [ ] **WS3:** A token estimate (no magic `batch_size` constant) decides verify chunking, reusing\n      `largest_window_tokens` + `est_tokens`.\n- [ ] **WS3:** The fit test is `est_tokens(request) + projected_output <= floor(window * HEADROOM)`,\n      where `HEADROOM` is the config knob `verify.verify_window_headroom` (default 0.8) and\n      `projected_output = len(chunk) * PER_FINDING_VERIFY_TOKENS` (a named per-finding reserve).\n- [ ] **WS3:** `<= budget` findings → one aggregate verify call (unchanged behavior).\n- [ ] **WS3:** `> budget` findings → minimal principled splits that preserve global enumeration and\n      re-merge verifications by finding `index`; a test (via a deterministic window-shrink seam)\n      asserts principled splitting, NOT count-12.\n- [ ] **WS3:** The `> budget` test also asserts the chars/4 estimate plus headroom keeps a real\n      request under the actual model window (the estimator safety margin is grounded, not assumed).\n- [ ] **WS3:** A single finding larger than the budget escalates from the resolved verify model via\n      `models_at_or_above`; if still too large at the top of the ladder it is marked INDETERMINATE\n      (non-blocking, surfaced) — never silently dropped; a test covers this path.\n- [ ] **WS4:** The workflow `coach_notes` step is gated on `surviving > 0`; a PASS with 0 surviving\n      advisories makes no coach LLM call; a test asserts the call count.\n- [ ] Each of WS1–WS4 is a child ticket of this epic, separately plan-reviewed before it is claimed.\n- [ ] `make lint` + `make check` + the full test suite pass.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782581294108228001,"uuid":"dbbed0ce-2d1c-46d4-9f4e-5ef8a82cea90"}